bib_record.title: Cross sections relevant to gamma-ray line emission in solar flares: 3-He-induced reactions on 16-O nuclei

free_txt: Institut de Physique Nucleaire
The experiment was performed at the
tandem accelerator of the IPN-Orsay.
The importance of studied lines as diagnosis for the
presence and properties of accelerated 3He in solar
flares is discussed in light of the measured cross
sections.
The gamma-rays were detected with four large
volume, high purity Ge detectors with bgo shielding for
Compton suppression.

The experiment was performed at the
tandem accelerator of the IPN-Orsay.
The beam current was integrated in a Faraday
cup located 1.4 meters behind the target.
Typical beam intensities were 10-20 nA.
From Ebeam=3.7 to 7.25 MeV and at 9 and 10 MeV, a
tantalum-oxide target (chemical composition  Ta2O5) of
800 mug/cm2 evaporated on a carbon foil backing of 90
mug/cm2 was used.  Above 7.25 MeV, two Ta2O5 targets of
1.5 mg/cm2 evaporated on carbon foils of 130 mug/cm2,
as well as two selfsupporting Mylar foils (chemical
composition C10H8O4) of 3.213 mg/cm2 (23 mumeters)
for Ebeam=12.5, 18, 21, 25, 30 and 36 MeV were used.
The thicknesses of the Ta2O5 targets were chosen for
the 3He energy loss in the targets to be similar to the
beam energy steps of 250 KeV below 10 MeV, in order to
avoid significant gaps in the excitation functions.
The reason of using Mylar targets instead of Ta2O5
targets at the highest energies was to avoid a too
intense production of neutrons and gamma-rays from
reactions with the Ta nuclei.  Repeated measurements at
the same energies allowed to ensure the stability of
the various targets.  After the experiment, the
thickness of one of the Ta2O5 targets was checked by a
Rutherford backscattering measurement.
The error bars only contain the
angular-dependent uncertainties and are obtained from a
quadratic sum of the error in the number of detected

Below 15 MeV, average values were generally
obtained from linear interpolations between adjacent
data points.  At higher energies, authors performed
fits to the cross section data by polynomial or
exponential curves.  They estimated the uncertainty
induced by this procedure to be generally negligible as
compared with the overall errors in the measured cross
sections.
